response:
Denote by (\(a,b)\) the length and width of the interior rectangle of the frame.  The picture frame has one-inch-wide pieces of wood so these lengths and this width differ by two.  Let's draw a picture.</think>
[asy]
size(5cm,5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
draw((0,0)--(5,0)--(5,7)--(0,7)--(0,0));

draw((1,1)--(4,1)--(4,6)--(1,6)--(1,1));

fill(((1,1)--(4,1)--(4,6)--(1,6)--cycle),darkblue);

draw (shift(0, 0.5)*((0,7)--(5,7)), linewidth(linewidth(0.7)));

draw(shift(0, -0.5)*((4,0)--(5,0)), linewidth(linewidth(0.7)));

draw(shift(0.5,0)*((5,0)--(5,1)), linewidth(linewidth(0.7)));
label("(\(a,b\))",(2.5,7.5),N);
label("(\(a+b\))",(2.5, 6.5),N);
[/asy]
$$a+b+2=5\tag{1}\label{eq1}$$
The area of the frame is equal to the area of the picture frame minus the area of the picture frame in the interior of frame: $$18=(a+2)(b+2)-ab\tag{2}\label{eq2}$$
Using \eqref{eq1} to solve the above equation for $a$: $$a=3\tag{3}\label{eq3}$$
Using \eqref{eq1} to solve the above equation for $b$: $$b=2\tag{4}\label{eq4}$$

The perimeter of the picture frame in the interior of frame is $$2a+2b=2(3)+2(2)=10\tag{5}\label{eq5}$$

